{{Infobox website | name = Live Music Archive | logo = [[Image:Livemusicarchive.png|150px|etree logo]] | screenshot = Screenshotlivemusicarchive.jpg | screenshot_size = 200px | caption = The LMA in June 2008 | url = [https://archive.org/details/etree www.archive.org/details/etree] | commercial = No | type = [[Live music]] trading | registration = Optional | owner = Internet Archive | author = Brewster Kahle | launch date = 1996 | current status = Active | revenue = }}
The '''Live Music Archive''' ('''LMA'''), part of the [[Internet Archive]], is an ad-free collection of over 170,000 concert recordings in [[Lossless data compression|lossless audio]] formats.<ref>{{cite news | first=J.D. | last=Biersdorfer | coauthors= | title=Take Along the Music in All Its Many Formats | date=2004-09-16 | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/16/technology/circuits/16askk.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2008-04-05 | language = }}</ref> The songs are also downloadable or playable in lossy formats such as [[Vorbis|Ogg Vorbis]] or [[MP3]]. The website is known for its extensive collection of [[Grateful Dead]] recordings,<ref>{{cite news | first=Jeff | last=Leeds | coauthors= | title=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/30/arts/music/30dead.html | date=2005-11-30 | publisher=The New York Times | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/30/arts/music/30dead.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2008-04-05 | language = }}</ref> and contains music from many other bands.
==History==
The collection increases in size due to the contribution of concert recordings by [[etree]] participants.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jake | last=Coyle | coauthors= | title=On the Net: Concerts on the Web | date= 2007-02-27| publisher=[[USA Today]] | url =https://www.usatoday.com/life/theater/2007-02-27-2627941010_x.htm | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2008-04-05 | language = }}</ref>
==Artists==
The majority of artists are [[jam band]]s.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jon | last=Parales | coauthors= | title=No Fears: Laptop D.J.'s Have a Feast | date=2004-09-10 | publisher=The New York Times | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/10/arts/music/10INTE.html?pagewanted=print | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2008-04-05 | language = }}</ref> Others include [[The Smashing Pumpkins]], [[Tenacious D]], [[Warren Zevon]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Tirpack |first=Alex |title=Warren Zevon live shows hit the web, possible film in the works |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/warren-zevon-live-shows-hit-the-web-possible-film-in-the-works-20090603 |work=Rolling Stone |date=June 3, 2009 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202232253/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/warren-zevon-live-shows-hit-the-web-possible-film-in-the-works-20090603 |archivedate=February 2, 2013 }}</ref> [[Ween]], [[Little Feat]].<ref name="''Glide'' Little Feat & Phish review">{{cite web|url=http://www.glidemagazine.com/hiddentrack/boot-camp-live-little-feat/|title=Boot Camp: Live Little Feat|last=Bernstein|first=Scott|date=2010-11-04|work=Hidden Track article review|publisher=''Glide Magazine''|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> and smaller independent bands.
